{"title_page": "Ulladakkam", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ulladakkam\n| image          = Ulladakkam film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Poster designed by [[Gayathri Ashokan]]\n| director       = [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]\n| producer       = [[Suresh Balaje]] \n| screenplay     = [[P. Balachandran]]\n| story          = [[Cheriyan Kalpakavadi]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mohanlal]]<br>[[Shobana]]<br>[[Amala (actress)|Amala]]<br>[[Murali (Malayalam actor)|Murali]]\n| music          = [[Ouseppachan]]\n| cinematography = [[Saloo George]]\n| editing        = K. Rajagopal\n| studio         = Sithara Combines\n| distributor    = Bhavachithra<br>Murali Films Release\n| released       = 1991\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Ulladakkam''''' ({{Translation|Content}}) is 1991 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]] and written by [[P. Balachandran]] from a story by [[Cheriyan Kalpakavadi]]. It stars [[Mohanlal]], [[Shobana]] and [[Amala (actress)|Amala]]. The film, produced by [[Suresh Balaje]] features a soundtrack composed by [[Ouseppachan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rajitha|title=Gossip from the southern film industry|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/14spice.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=19 February 2017|date=14 June 2000}}</ref> The plot follows a psychiatrist, Dr. Sunny (Mohanlal) and one of his patients, Reshma (Amala), who gets obsessed with him romantically, but Sunny is already engaged with Annie (Shobana).\n\nUpon release, it received critical acclaim and was also a commercial success at the box office.<ref name=TH1/><ref name=BW/> ''Ulladakkam'' is now regarded as one of the best films of Kamal.<ref name=TH2/> The film won three [[Kerala State Film Awards]], including [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (Mohanlal), [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]], and [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Dubbing Artist|Best Dubbing Artist]] ([[Bhagyalakshmi]]). Amala won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Malayalam]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2019}}\nDr Sunny is a psychiatrist who is engaged to his girlfriend Annie. One day a girl named Reshma is admitted to Sunny's hospital by her brother Roy, who is a close friend of Sunny. Gradually, Sunny finds out that she was traumatized after witnessing her boyfriend getting beaten to death by some of his colleagues. Sunny helps her to recover, but soon Reshma becomes obsessed with Sunny and falls in love with him.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mohanlal]] as Dr. Sunny Joseph\n*[[Shobana]] as Annie, Sunny's fiance (Voice dubbed by [[Anandavally]])\n*[[Amala (actress)|Amala]] as Reshma, Sunny's patient (Voice dubbed by [[Bhagyalakshmi]])\n*[[Murali (Malayalam actor)|Murali]] as Roy\n*[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Kishore\n*[[M. G. Soman]] as Mathachan\n*[[Sukumari]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]] as Kunjachan\n*[[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Sunny's Mother\n*[[Philomina]] as Hospital Attendant\n*[[Jagathy Sreekumar]] as Burning Desire - Mental Patient\n*[[Zainuddin (actor)|Zainuddin]] as Chakrapani\n*[[Krishnan Kutty Nair (actor)|Krishnan Kutty Nair]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Mavelikkara Ponnamma]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Kunchan (actor)|Kunchan]] as Freddy\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]] as Doctor\n* [[Zeenath]] as Reena (Voice dubbed by [[Anandavally]])\n\n==Other crew==\n* Art director: Roy P. Thomas\n* Production controller: M. Salim\n* [[Assistant director]]: [[Lal Jose]], [[Dileep (actor)|Dileep]], Akbar\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Ulladakkam\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Ouseppachan]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|1991|7|14}}\n| recorded   = 1991\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Popular music]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=17|s=35}}\n| language   = [[Malayalam]]\n| label      = Ranjini Cassettes\n| producer   = [[Suresh Balaje]]\n| prev_title = [[Thoovalsparsham]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Aavanikunnile Kinnaripookkal]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n[[Ouseppachan]] composed the soundtrack for the film, to which the lyrics were written by [[Kaithapram Damodaran Namboothiri]]. The original soundtrack consisting four tracks was released by Ranjini Cassettes on 14 July 1991.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ranjini Cassettes|title=Ulladakkam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) - EP by Ouseppachan on Apple Music|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/ulladakkam-original-motion/id1030109279|publisher=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=14 July 1991}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Ulladakkam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = {{Duration|m=17|s=35}}\n\n| title1 = Andhiveyil\n| extra1 = [[K. J. Yesudas]], [[Sujatha Mohan]]\n| length1 = 04:00\n\n| title2 = Maayatha Marivil\n| extra2 = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length2 = 04:49\n\n| title3 = Paathiramazha (Female vocals)\n| extra3 = [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length3 = 04:24\n\n| title4 = Paathiramazha\n| extra4 = K. J. Yesudas\n| length4 = 04:22\n}}\n\n==Awards==\n;[[Kerala State Film Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Kerala State Chalachitra Academy]]|title=State Film Awards - 1991|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards3.htm|publisher=[[Department of Information and Public Relations (Kerala)|Department of Information and Public Relations]]|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=1991|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234157/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards3.htm|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] - [[Mohanlal]]\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]] - [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Dubbing Artist|Best Dubbing Artist]] - [[Bhagyalakshmi]]\n\n;[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Malayalam|Best Actress (Malayalam)]] - [[Amala (actress)|Amala]]\n\n;[[Kerala Film Critics Association Awards]]\n* Best Actor - Mohanlal\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0292300}}\n\n{{Kamal (director)}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kamal (director)]]\n[[Category:Films set in psychiatric hospitals]]\n[[Category:Medical-themed films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ulladakkam\n| image          = Ulladakkam film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Poster designed by [[Gayathri Ashokan]]\n| director       = [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]\n| producer       = [[Suresh Balaje]] \n| screenplay     = [[P. Balachandran]]\n| story          = [[Cheriyan Kalpakavadi]]\n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Mohanlal]]<br>[[Shobana]]<br>[[Amala (actress)|Amala]]<br>[[Murali (Malayalam actor)|Murali]]\n| music          = [[Ouseppachan]]\n| cinematography = [[Saloo George]]\n| editing        = K. Rajagopal\n| studio         = Sithara Combines\n| distributor    = Bhavachithra<br>Murali Films Release\n| released       = 1991\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Ulladakkam''''' ({{Translation|Content}}) is 1991 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]] and written by [[P. Balachandran]] from a story by [[Cheriyan Kalpakavadi]]. It stars [[Mohanlal]], [[Shobana]] and [[Amala (actress)|Amala]]. The film, produced by [[Suresh Balaje]] features a soundtrack composed by [[Ouseppachan]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rajitha|title=Gossip from the southern film industry|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/14spice.htm|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=19 February 2017|date=14 June 2000}}</ref> The plot follows a psychiatrist, Dr. Sunny (Mohanlal) and one of his patients, Reshma (Amala), who gets obsessed with him romantically, but Sunny is already engaged with Annie (Shobana).\n\nUpon release, it received critical acclaim and was also a commercial success at the box office.<ref name=TH1/><ref name=BW/> ''Ulladakkam'' is now regarded as one of the best films of Kamal.<ref name=TH2/> The film won three [[Kerala State Film Awards]], including [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (Mohanlal), [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]], and [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Dubbing Artist|Best Dubbing Artist]] ([[Bhagyalakshmi]]). Amala won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Malayalam]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{Expand section|date=July 2019}}\nDr Sunny is a psychiatrist who is engaged to his girlfriend Annie. One day a girl named Reshma is admitted to Sunny's hospital by her brother Roy, who is a close friend of Sunny. Gradually, Sunny finds out that she was traumatized after witnessing her boyfriend getting beaten to death by some of his colleagues. Sunny helps her to recover, but soon Reshma becomes obsessed with Sunny and falls in love with him.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mohanlal]] as Dr. Sunny Joseph\n*[[Shobana]] as Annie, Sunny's fiance (Voice dubbed by [[Anandavally]])\n*[[Amala (actress)|Amala]] as Reshma, Sunny's patient (Voice dubbed by [[Bhagyalakshmi]])\n*[[Murali (Malayalam actor)|Murali]] as Roy\n*[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Kishore\n*[[M. G. Soman]] as Mathachan\n*[[Sukumari]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Innocent (actor)|Innocent]] as Kunjachan\n*[[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Sunny's Mother\n*[[Philomina]] as Hospital Attendant\n*[[Jagathy Sreekumar]] as Burning Desire - Mental Patient\n*[[Zainuddin (actor)|Zainuddin]] as Chakrapani\n*[[Krishnan Kutty Nair (actor)|Krishnan Kutty Nair]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Mavelikkara Ponnamma]] as Mental Patient\n*[[Kunchan (actor)|Kunchan]] as Freddy\n*[[T. P. Madhavan]] as Doctor\n* [[Zeenath]] as Reena (Voice dubbed by [[Anandavally]])\n\n==Other crew==\n* Art director: Roy P. Thomas\n* Production controller: M. Salim\n* [[Assistant director]]: [[Lal Jose]], [[Dileep (actor)|Dileep]], Akbar\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Ulladakkam\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Ouseppachan]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|1991|7|14}}\n| recorded   = 1991\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Popular music]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=17|s=35}}\n| language   = [[Malayalam]]\n| label      = Ranjini Cassettes\n| producer   = [[Suresh Balaje]]\n| prev_title = [[Thoovalsparsham]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Aavanikunnile Kinnaripookkal]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n}}\n[[Ouseppachan]] composed the soundtrack for the film, to which the lyrics were written by [[Kaithapram Damodaran Namboothiri]]. The original soundtrack consisting four tracks was released by Ranjini Cassettes on 14 July 1991.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ranjini Cassettes|title=Ulladakkam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) - EP by Ouseppachan on Apple Music|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/ulladakkam-original-motion/id1030109279|publisher=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=14 July 1991}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Ulladakkam (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = {{Duration|m=17|s=35}}\n\n| title1 = Andhiveyil\n| extra1 = [[K. J. Yesudas]], [[Sujatha Mohan]]\n| length1 = 04:00\n\n| title2 = Maayatha Marivil\n| extra2 = [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length2 = 04:49\n\n| title3 = Paathiramazha (Female vocals)\n| extra3 = [[K. S. Chithra]]\n| length3 = 04:24\n\n| title4 = Paathiramazha\n| extra4 = K. J. Yesudas\n| length4 = 04:22\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nUpon release, it received critical acclaim and was also a commercial success at the box office.<ref name=TH1>{{cite news|last=Nazeer|first=Mohamed|title=An unsound trend in Mollywood|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/an-unsound-trend-in-mollywood/article8010107.ece|accessdate=19 February 2017|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=20 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=BW>{{cite web|last=Thanveer|title=Amala Akkineni returns to Mollywood for Antony Sony's next|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-16/amala-akkineni-returns-to-mollywood-for-antony-sonys-next.html|publisher=Behindwoods.com|accessdate=19 February 2017|date=6 November 2016}}</ref> ''Ulladakkam'' is now regarded as one of the best films of Kamal.<ref name=TH2>{{cite news|title=Happy man|url=http://www.thehindu.com/lf/2003/04/23/stories/2003042301770200.htm|accessdate=19 February 2017|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=23 April 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n;[[Kerala State Film Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Kerala State Chalachitra Academy]]|title=State Film Awards - 1991|url=http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards3.htm|publisher=[[Department of Information and Public Relations (Kerala)|Department of Information and Public Relations]]|accessdate=11 February 2017|date=1991|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234157/http://www.prd.kerala.gov.in/stateawards3.htm|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] - [[Mohanlal]]\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]] - [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]\n* [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Dubbing Artist|Best Dubbing Artist]] - [[Bhagyalakshmi]]\n\n;[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n* [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress \u2013 Malayalam|Best Actress (Malayalam)]] - [[Amala (actress)|Amala]]\n\n;[[Kerala Film Critics Association Awards]]\n* Best Actor - Mohanlal\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0292300}}\n\n{{Kama